  {id:"fre8l3",title:"Les nombres 20-100",icon:"🔢",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Les nombres de 20 à 100",desc:"French numbers have quirks: 70 = soixante-dix (60+10), 80 = quatre-vingts (4x20), 90 = quatre-vingt-dix (4x20+10). This is the Belgian/Swiss system's rival!",goals:["Count from 20 to 100","Handle the 70/80/90 system","Use numbers for prices and addresses"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"vingt",src:"twenty (20)",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"VAN",note:"20. Final -t is normally silent.\nBut: vingt et un (21), the t links.",example:"A: Ça coûte combien?\nB: Vingt euros.\nA: D'accord, voilà.",exampleSrc:"A: How much does it cost?\nB: Twenty euros.\nA: OK, here you go.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"trente",src:"thirty (30)",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"TRAHNT",note:"30. Regular pattern.\n31 = trente et un.\n32 = trente-deux... etc.",example:"A: Il y a combien d'élèves?\nB: Trente élèves dans la classe.\nA: C'est beaucoup!",exampleSrc:"A: How many students are there?\nB: Thirty students in the class.\nA: That's a lot!",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"quarante",src:"forty (40)",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"kah-RAHNT",note:"40. Regular pattern continues.\n41 = quarante et un.\n45 = quarante-cinq.",example:"A: Tu as quel âge?\nB: J'ai quarante ans.\nA: Tu ne les fais pas!",exampleSrc:"A: How old are you?\nB: I'm forty.\nA: You don't look it!",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"cinquante",src:"fifty (50)",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"san-KAHNT",note:"50. From cinq (5).\n51 = cinquante et un.\n55 = cinquante-cinq.",example:"A: Le loyer est de cinquante euros par semaine?\nB: Non, cinq cents euros par mois!\nA: Ah, c'est différent!",exampleSrc:"A: The rent is fifty euros per week?\nB: No, five hundred euros per month!\nA: Ah, that's different!",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"soixante",src:"sixty (60)",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"swah-SAHNT",note:"60. From six.\n61 = soixante et un.\n69 = soixante-neuf.",example:"A: Soixante euros pour cette chemise?\nB: C'est la qualité française!\nA: Bon, je la prends.",exampleSrc:"A: Sixty euros for this shirt?\nB: That's French quality!\nA: Fine, I'll take it.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"tip",title:"The 70-80-90 system",text:"Here's where French gets creative:\n\n70 = soixante-dix (60 + 10)\n71 = soixante et onze (60 + 11)\n72 = soixante-douze (60 + 12)\n\n80 = quatre-vingts (4 x 20)\n81 = quatre-vingt-un (no 'et', no -s on vingts)\n\n90 = quatre-vingt-dix (4 x 20 + 10)\n91 = quatre-vingt-onze\n99 = quatre-vingt-dix-neuf\n\n100 = cent"},
        {type:"teach",trg:"soixante-dix",src:"seventy (70)",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"swah-sahnt-DEES",note:"70 = 60 + 10. This is the standard French system.\nBelgium/Switzerland say septante.",example:"A: Combien?\nB: Soixante-dix euros.\nA: Soixante plus dix, oui!",exampleSrc:"A: How much?\nB: Seventy euros.\nA: Sixty plus ten, yes!",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"quatre-vingts",src:"eighty (80)",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"KAH-truh VAN",note:"80 = 4 x 20. Note the -s on vingts.\nBut: 81 = quatre-vingt-un (no -s).",example:"A: Mon grand-père a quatre-vingts ans.\nB: Quatre fois vingt!\nA: Il est en pleine forme.",exampleSrc:"A: My grandfather is eighty.\nB: Four times twenty!\nA: He's in great shape.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"cent",src:"one hundred (100)",pos:"num",gender:null,phonetic:"SAHN",note:"100. No article needed.\nDeux cents = 200 (with -s).\nDeux cent dix = 210 (no -s before another number).",example:"A: Ça fait cent euros.\nB: Cent euros! C'est cher.\nA: C'est la qualité.",exampleSrc:"A: That comes to a hundred euros.\nB: A hundred euros! That's expensive.\nA: It's quality.",funFact:"French numbers are mostly regular, except 70-99 which use a base-20 system from Celtic roots."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"vingt",src:"20"},{trg:"trente",src:"30"},{trg:"quarante",src:"40"},{trg:"cinquante",src:"50"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"70 in French is 'soixante-dix', which literally means:",opts:["Sixty-ten","Seventy","Seven-ten","Sixty plus seven"],ans:"Sixty-ten",hint:"Soixante = 60, dix = 10. Added together."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["vingts","vingt","cents","dix"],hint:"4 x 20. Note: the final word has an -s when standing alone.",s:"Quatre-{1} = 80.",a:"vingts"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"soixante-dix",src:"70"},{trg:"quatre-vingts",src:"80"},{trg:"quatre-vingt-dix",src:"90"},{trg:"cent",src:"100"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"81 is 'quatre-vingt-UN' (no -s on vingt). Why?",opts:["It sounds better","Vingt drops -s before another number","81 is odd","It is a rule without reason"],ans:"Vingt drops -s before another number",hint:"Quatre-___s (80) but quatre-___-un (81). The -s disappears when followed by more."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["dix","neuf","onze","vingt"],hint:"80 + 10 = 90. Which number means ten?",s:"Quatre-vingt-{1} = 90.",a:"dix"},
        {type:"mc",q:"What is 75 in French?",opts:["Septante-cinq","Soixante-cinq","Soixante-quinze","Quatre-vingt-quinze"],ans:"Soixante-quinze",hint:"60 + 15 = 75. ___ = 15."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["cent","cents","san","cen"],hint:"One hundred. No article, no -s for exactly 100.",s:"Ça coûte {1} euros. (100)",a:"cent"}
  ]},
  {id:"fre8l4",title:"Faire les courses",icon:"🛒",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Faire les courses: shopping",desc:"Learn essential shopping phrases for French stores. How to ask prices, sizes, try things on, and complete a purchase.",goals:["Ask for prices","Request sizes","Use shopping phrases fluently"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"Combien ça coûte?",src:"How much does it cost?",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"kom-bee-AN sah KOOT",note:"The essential price question.\nAlternatives: C'est combien?\nÇa fait combien?",example:"A: Combien ça coûte, ce pantalon?\nB: Quarante-cinq euros.\nA: C'est un bon prix.",exampleSrc:"A: How much do these pants cost?\nB: Forty-five euros.\nA: That's a good price.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"Je voudrais...",src:"I would like...",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"zhuh voo-DRAY",note:"Polite way to ask for something.\nMore polite than je veux (I want).\nConditional of vouloir.",example:"A: Bonjour, je voudrais essayer cette robe.\nB: Bien sûr, quelle taille?\nA: Du 38.",exampleSrc:"A: Hello, I would like to try on this dress.\nB: Of course, what size?\nA: Size 38.",funFact:"French verbs change form for each person. The spoken forms are often simpler than the written ones."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"essayer",src:"to try on",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"eh-say-YAY",note:"Regular -er verb (with spelling change).\nLa cabine d'essayage = fitting room.",example:"A: Je peux essayer ce manteau?\nB: Oui, la cabine est là-bas.\nA: Merci!",exampleSrc:"A: Can I try on this coat?\nB: Yes, the fitting room is over there.\nA: Thanks!",funFact:"A regular -er verb, the most common French verb group (~90% of all verbs)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"C'est trop cher",src:"It's too expensive",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"say troh SHEHR",note:"Trop = too (much). Cher = expensive.\nFeminine: chère. Les soldes = sales.",example:"A: Cette veste coûte deux cents euros.\nB: C'est trop cher!\nA: Il y a des soldes la semaine prochaine.",exampleSrc:"A: This jacket costs two hundred euros.\nB: That's too expensive!\nA: There are sales next week.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"Je le/la prends",src:"I'll take it",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"zhuh luh/lah PRAHN",note:"Le = it (masc.), la = it (fem.).\nJe le prends = I take it (masc.).\nJe la prends = I take it (fem.).",example:"A: Le pantalon vous va bien.\nB: Oui, je le prends!\nA: Très bien, je vous emballe ça.",exampleSrc:"A: The pants suit you well.\nB: Yes, I'll take them!\nA: Very well, I'll wrap that up.",funFact:"French verbs change form for each person. The spoken forms are often simpler than the written ones."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"payer",src:"to pay",pos:"verb",gender:null,phonetic:"pay-YAY",note:"Regular -er verb (spelling change: y->i).\nPayer par carte = pay by card.\nPayer en espèces = pay cash.",example:"A: Comment vous payez?\nB: Par carte, s'il vous plaît.\nA: Voilà, merci et bonne journée!",exampleSrc:"A: How are you paying?\nB: By card, please.\nA: There you go, thanks and have a good day!",funFact:"A regular -er verb, the most common French verb group (~90% of all verbs)."},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Combien ça coûte?' asks about:",opts:["The price","The color","The size","The material"],ans:"The price",hint:"Combien = how much. This question is about money."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["voudrais","veux","vouloir","veut"],hint:"I would like: the polite conditional form.",s:"Je {1} essayer cette chemise.",a:"voudrais"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Combien ça coûte?",src:"How much?"},{trg:"Je voudrais",src:"I would like"},{trg:"essayer",src:"to try on"},{trg:"C'est trop cher",src:"Too expensive"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Je le prends' uses 'le' because:",opts:["It is polite","The item is masculine","The item is expensive","Le means 'this'"],ans:"The item is masculine",hint:"Le replaces a ___ noun. La would replace a feminine one."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["payez","payer","payons","payes"],hint:"How do you pay? Vous + which form of the verb?",s:"Comment vous {1}? Par carte ou en espèces?",a:"payez"},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Les soldes' in France are:",opts:["Taxes","Returns","Sales / discounts","Receipts"],ans:"Sales / discounts",hint:"The period when shops reduce prices. Happens twice yearly."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["trop","très","un peu","assez"],hint:"It's TOO expensive. Which word means 'too much'?",s:"C'est {1} cher, je ne le prends pas.",a:"trop"},
        {type:"mc",q:"'La cabine d'essayage' is:",opts:["The cash register","The exit","The display window","The fitting room"],ans:"The fitting room",hint:"Essayage comes from essayer. Where do you try clothes on?"},
        {type:"fb",opts:["la","le","les","l'"],hint:"Robe is feminine. Which pronoun replaces a feminine noun?",s:"Cette robe me va bien. Je {1} prends!",a:"la"},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Payer en espèces' means to pay:",opts:["In cash","By check","By card","Online"],ans:"In cash",hint:"Espèces = species, but in money context = physical ___."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["je","tu","il","nous"],hint:"I would like: first person subject pronoun.",s:"Bonjour, {1} voudrais une jupe bleue.",a:"je"}
  ]},
  {id:"fre8l5",title:"Les démonstratifs",icon:"👆",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Ce, cet, cette, ces: this/that/these/those",desc:"Demonstrative adjectives point at things: THIS shirt, THAT dress, THESE shoes. French has four forms based on gender and number.",goals:["Use ce (masc.), cette (fem.), ces (plural)","Know when to use cet (before vowel)","Point at items while shopping"]},
        {type:"tip",title:"Demonstrative adjectives",text:"ce + masculine noun: ce pantalon (this/that pants)\ncet + masculine noun starting with vowel/h: cet homme\ncette + feminine noun: cette robe (this/that dress)\nces + any plural: ces chaussures (these/those shoes)\n\nFrench does not distinguish this/that.\nBoth = ce/cette/ces.\nTo specify: add -ci (this) or -là (that) after the noun."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"ce",src:"this / that (masculine)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",phonetic:"SUH",note:"Before masculine nouns starting with consonant.\nCe pantalon, ce chapeau, ce magasin.",example:"A: Tu aimes ce manteau?\nB: Ce manteau noir? Oui!\nA: Il coûte cinquante euros.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you like this coat?\nB: This black coat? Yes!\nA: It costs fifty euros.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"cet",src:"this / that (masc. before vowel)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",phonetic:"SET",note:"Before masculine nouns starting with vowel or silent h.\nCet appartement, cet hôtel.",example:"A: Tu connais cet homme?\nB: Non, qui est-ce?\nA: C'est mon voisin.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know this man?\nB: No, who is he?\nA: He's my neighbor.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"cette",src:"this / that (feminine)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",phonetic:"SET",note:"Before all feminine singular nouns.\nCette chemise, cette jupe, cette couleur.",example:"A: Regarde cette robe!\nB: Elle est magnifique.\nA: Et pas chère!",exampleSrc:"A: Look at this dress!\nB: It's magnificent.\nA: And not expensive!",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"ces",src:"these / those (plural)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",phonetic:"SAY",note:"Before all plural nouns (masc. or fem.).\nCes pantalons, ces robes, ces couleurs.",example:"A: Ces chaussures sont jolies.\nB: Oui, mais ces chaussures sont chères.\nA: C'est vrai.",exampleSrc:"A: These shoes are pretty.\nB: Yes, but these shoes are expensive.\nA: That's true.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"ce...ci / ce...là",src:"this one here / that one there",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"see / lah",note:"To distinguish this vs that:\n-ci = here (this)\n-là = there (that)\nAdded after the noun.",example:"A: Quelle robe? Cette robe-ci ou cette robe-là?\nB: Cette robe-ci, la bleue.\nA: Bon choix!",exampleSrc:"A: Which dress? This one here or that one there?\nB: This one here, the blue one.\nA: Good choice!",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"mc",q:"Before a feminine noun, you use:",opts:["Cette","Cet","Ce","Ces"],ans:"Cette",hint:"Feminine singular always uses the same form, regardless of first letter."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Ce","Cet","Cette","Ces"],hint:"Pantalon is masculine, starts with consonant.",s:"{1} pantalon est trop grand.",a:"Ce"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"ce manteau",src:"this coat"},{trg:"cette robe",src:"this dress"},{trg:"ces chaussures",src:"these shoes"},{trg:"cet homme",src:"this man"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Cet' is used instead of 'ce' when:",opts:["The noun is feminine","The noun starts with a vowel or silent h","The noun is plural","The noun is long"],ans:"The noun starts with a vowel or silent h",hint:"Masculine before ___/h uses a special form for pronunciation."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Cette","Ce","Cet","Ces"],hint:"Chemise is feminine singular. Which demonstrative?",s:"{1} chemise est très jolie.",a:"Cette"},
        {type:"mc",q:"To say 'THAT dress there' (pointing far), you add:",opts:["-ci after robe","-ici after robe","-là after robe","-bas after robe"],ans:"-là after robe",hint:"Là = there. Added to the noun to specify distance."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Ces","Ce","Cette","Cet"],hint:"Shoes is plural. Which demonstrative for plural?",s:"{1} chaussures sont en solde.",a:"Ces"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"ce pantalon-ci",src:"these pants here"},{trg:"cette robe-là",src:"that dress there"},{trg:"ces chaussures-ci",src:"these shoes here"},{trg:"cet hôtel-là",src:"that hotel there"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Cet appartement' uses 'cet' because appartement is:",opts:["Feminine","Plural","Masculine starting with a consonant","Masculine starting with a vowel"],ans:"Masculine starting with a vowel",hint:"Appartement is ___ and begins with 'a' (a ___)."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["ce","cet","cette","ces"],hint:"Manteau is masculine, starts with consonant. Same form both times.",s:"Tu préfères {1} manteau-ci ou ___ manteau-là?",a:["ce","ce"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"French demonstratives (ce/cette/ces) cover:",opts:["Both 'this' and 'that'","Only 'that'","Only 'this'","Only 'these'"],ans:"Both 'this' and 'that'",hint:"French does not have separate words for this/that by default."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre8l6",title:"100 à 1000",icon:"💯",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Les nombres de 100 à 1000",desc:"Master large numbers for prices, addresses, and dates. French numbers above 100 follow a simpler pattern than 70-90.",goals:["Count in hundreds","Say numbers up to 1000","Use numbers for prices"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"cent",src:"one hundred (100)",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"SAHN",note:"100. No un before cent.\nDeux cents = 200 (with -s).\nDeux cent dix = 210 (no -s).",example:"A: Ça coûte cent euros.\nB: Cent exactement?\nA: Cent virgule cinquante.",exampleSrc:"A: It costs 100 euros.\nB: Exactly 100?\nA: 100.50.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"deux cents",src:"two hundred (200)",pos:"num",gender:null,phonetic:"duh SAHN",note:"200. Cents gets -s when it ends the number.\nBut: deux cent dix (210) = no -s.\nRule: -s only if nothing follows.",example:"A: Le loyer est de deux cents euros?\nB: Non, cinq cents!\nA: C'est cher...",exampleSrc:"A: Is the rent 200 euros?\nB: No, 500!\nA: That's expensive...",funFact:"French numbers are mostly regular, except 70-99 which use a base-20 system from Celtic roots."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"mille",src:"one thousand (1000)",pos:"noun",gender:null,phonetic:"MEEL",note:"1000. Never takes -s.\nDeux mille = 2000 (no -s on mille).\nMille is invariable.",example:"A: Cet appartement coûte mille euros par mois.\nB: Mille euros!\nA: C'est Paris...",exampleSrc:"A: This apartment costs 1000 euros per month.\nB: A thousand euros!\nA: It's Paris...",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Number patterns 100-1000",text:"100 = cent\n200 = deux cents (with -s)\n201 = deux cent un (no -s)\n300 = trois cents\n500 = cinq cents\n999 = neuf cent quatre-vingt-dix-neuf\n1000 = mille\n\nRule: cents takes -s ONLY at the end.\nMille NEVER takes -s."},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Deux cents' has an -s, but 'deux cent dix' does not because:",opts:["The -s drops when another number follows","210 is odd","It is a mistake","Dix removes the -s"],ans:"The -s drops when another number follows",hint:"Cents gets -s only when it's the last ___ word."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["cents","cent","cen","centes"],hint:"500 ends on the hundreds. Does cent get an -s here?",s:"Cinq {1} euros. (500)",a:"cents"},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Mille' never takes -s. So 3000 is:",opts:["Trois milles","Trois mille","Troi mille","Trois mill"],ans:"Trois mille",hint:"___ is invariable, unlike cent."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["mille","mill","cent","cents"],hint:"One thousand. The word that never changes.",s:"Cet ordinateur coûte {1} euros. (1000)",a:"mille"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"cent",src:"100"},{trg:"deux cents",src:"200"},{trg:"cinq cents",src:"500"},{trg:"mille",src:"1000"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"What is 350 in French?",opts:["Trois cents cinquante","Trois cinquante","Trois cent cinquante","Trente-cinq cent"],ans:"Trois cent cinquante",hint:"300 + 50. Since 50 follows, ___ has no -s."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["soixante","septante","soixante-dix","quarante"],hint:"75 = the 60-system. What base number starts the combo?",s:"Trois cent {1}-cinq euros. (375)",a:"soixante"},
        {type:"mc",q:"999 in French is:",opts:["Neuf neuf neuf","Neuf cents quatre-vingt-dix-neuf","Neuf cent neuf neuf","Neuf cent quatre-vingt-dix-neuf"],ans:"Neuf cent quatre-vingt-dix-neuf",hint:"900 + 90 + 9. No -s on ___ because more follows."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["mille","milles","cent","cents"],hint:"10,000. The word for 1000. It never takes -s.",s:"Cette voiture coûte dix {1} euros.",a:"mille"},
        {type:"mc",q:"How do you say 250 euros?",opts:["Deux cent cinquante","Deux cents cinquante","Vingt-cinq cent","Deux cinquante"],ans:"Deux cent cinquante",hint:"200 + 50. No -s on ___ when more follows."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["neuf","nouveau","huit","dix"],hint:"900 = ___ cent. Which number means nine?",s:"Il y a {1} cent habitants dans ce village. (900)",a:"neuf"},
        {type:"mc",q:"A common French salary might be 'deux mille cinq cents euros'. That's:",opts:["250 euros","2,500 euros","2,005 euros","25,000 euros"],ans:"2,500 euros",hint:"Deux mille = 2000. Cinq cents = 500. Total?"},
        {type:"fb",opts:["cent","cents","mille","milles"],hint:"630 = six ___ trente. Another number follows.",s:"Six {1} trente euros. (630)",a:"cent"}
  ]},
  {id:"fre8l7",title:"Au magasin",icon:"🏬",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Au magasin: at the store",desc:"Practice complete shopping scenarios. Combine clothing, colors, numbers, demonstratives, and shopping phrases in real conversations.",goals:["Navigate a complete shopping scenario","Use all Unit 8 vocabulary together","Handle prices and payments"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"Quelle taille?",src:"What size?",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"kel TAHY",note:"Taille = size (for clothes).\nPointure = size (for shoes).\nQuelle = which/what (fem.).",example:"A: Je voudrais cette chemise.\nB: Quelle taille, monsieur?\nA: Du 42.",exampleSrc:"A: I'd like this shirt.\nB: What size, sir?\nA: Size 42.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"Ça vous va?",src:"Does it suit you? / Does it fit?",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"sah voo VAH",note:"Va comes from aller.\nÇa te va? = informal version.\nUsed for both fit and style.",example:"A: Ce pantalon, ça vous va?\nB: Oui, c'est parfait!\nA: Excellent choix.",exampleSrc:"A: Do these pants fit you?\nB: Yes, it's perfect!\nA: Excellent choice.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"trop grand / trop petit",src:"too big / too small",pos:"adj",gender:null,phonetic:"troh GRAHN / troh puh-TEE",note:"Trop + adjective = too + adjective.\nTrop grand, trop cher, trop long.",example:"A: Ce manteau est trop grand.\nB: Essayez la taille en dessous.\nA: D'accord.",exampleSrc:"A: This coat is too big.\nB: Try the size below.\nA: OK.",funFact:"French adjectives agree in gender and number with their noun. Most add -e for feminine."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"Ça fait combien?",src:"How much does that come to?",pos:"intj",gender:null,phonetic:"sah fay kom-bee-AN",note:"At the register: total price question.\nÇa fait = that makes/comes to.\nEn tout = in total.",example:"A: Ça fait combien en tout?\nB: Quatre-vingt-quinze euros.\nA: Voilà ma carte.",exampleSrc:"A: How much does that come to in total?\nB: Ninety-five euros.\nA: Here's my card.",funFact:"French gave English roughly 30% of its vocabulary. Many formal English words have French origins."},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Ça vous va?' asks whether something:",opts:["Fits or suits you","Is expensive","Is available","Is on sale"],ans:"Fits or suits you",hint:"Va (from aller) here means to fit/suit someone."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Quelle","Quel","Quelles","Quels"],hint:"What size? Taille is feminine singular.",s:"{1} taille, s'il vous plaît?",a:"Quelle"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Quelle taille?",src:"What size?"},{trg:"Ça vous va?",src:"Does it fit?"},{trg:"trop grand",src:"too big"},{trg:"Ça fait combien?",src:"How much total?"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Cette jupe est trop petite' means the skirt is:",opts:["Too big","Too small","Too expensive","Too long"],ans:"Too small",hint:"Trop = ___. Petite = ___ (feminine form)."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["petit","grand","cher","noir"],hint:"The pants are too small. Need the next size UP.",s:"Ce pantalon est trop {1}. Vous avez la taille au-dessus?",a:"petit"},
        {type:"mc",q:"At the register, to ask the total you say:",opts:["Combien ça coûte?","C'est combien la taille?","Ça fait combien?","Vous avez combien?"],ans:"Ça fait combien?",hint:"Ça ___ = that comes to. For the total at checkout."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["fait","coûte","est","va"],hint:"That comes to 90 euros total. Which verb goes with ça?",s:"Ça {1} quatre-vingt-dix euros en tout.",a:"fait"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"payer par carte",src:"pay by card"},{trg:"payer en espèces",src:"pay cash"},{trg:"les soldes",src:"sales"},{trg:"la cabine d'essayage",src:"fitting room"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"A shop assistant asks 'Quelle pointure?' They want to know your:",opts:["Clothes size","Glove size","Hat size","Shoe size"],ans:"Shoe size",hint:"Pointure is specifically for footwear measurement."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["essayer","acheter","payer","porter"],hint:"I would like to try on this jacket. Which verb?",s:"Je voudrais {1} cette veste en noir.",a:"essayer"},
        {type:"mc",q:"You choose a shirt for 85 euros. In French, 85 is:",opts:["Quatre-vingt-cinq","Huitante-cinq","Soixante-vingt-cinq","Quatre-vingts-cinq"],ans:"Quatre-vingt-cinq",hint:"80 + 5. No -s on ___ because a number follows."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["me","te","se","nous"],hint:"These shoes please ME a lot. Which indirect pronoun?",s:"Ces chaussures {1} plaisent beaucoup!",a:"me"},
        {type:"mc",q:"After trying on clothes, to say 'I'll take it' for a feminine item:",opts:["Je le prends","Je la prends","Je les prends","Je prends"],ans:"Je la prends",hint:"Feminine items use the feminine direct object pronoun."}
  ]},
  {id:"fre8l8b",title:"Plus de Vêtements",icon:"🧥",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Plus de Vêtements",desc:"Expand your clothing vocabulary with jackets, scarves, boots, and more.",goals:["Learn 7 new clothing items","Understand plural-only clothing items","Practice un/une/des with clothing"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"une veste",src:"a jacket",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Une veste: a jacket (feminine).\nShorter than un manteau (a coat).",example:"A: Il fait froid aujourd'hui.\nB: Oui, je mets ma veste.",exampleSrc:"A: It's cold today.\nB: Yes, I'm putting on my jacket.",funFact:"Feminine noun. Words ending in -tion, -sion, -ure are usually feminine."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"un pull",src:"a sweater / pullover",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Un pull: a sweater (masculine).\nShort for un pullover.\nAlso: un sweat (a sweatshirt).",example:"A: Qu'est-ce que tu portes?\nB: Je porte un pull bleu.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you wearing?\nB: I'm wearing a blue sweater.",funFact:"Masculine noun. Words ending in -age, -ment, -isme are usually masculine."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"une écharpe",src:"a scarf",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Une écharpe: a scarf (feminine).\nWorn around the neck for warmth.",example:"A: Tu as froid?\nB: Un peu. Je prends mon écharpe.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you cold?\nB: A little. I'm taking my scarf.",funFact:"Feminine noun. Words ending in -tion, -sion, -ure are usually feminine."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"une ceinture",src:"a belt",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Une ceinture: a belt (feminine).\nAlso means seatbelt: la ceinture de sécurité.",example:"A: Ce pantalon est trop grand!\nB: Tu as besoin d'une ceinture.",exampleSrc:"A: These pants are too big!\nB: You need a belt.",funFact:"Feminine noun. Words ending in -tion, -sion, -ure are usually feminine."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"des chaussettes",src:"socks",pos:"noun",gender:"pl",note:"Des chaussettes: socks (feminine plural).\nOne sock: une chaussette.\nUsually used in the plural.",example:"A: Où sont mes chaussettes?\nB: Elles sont sous le lit.",exampleSrc:"A: Where are my socks?\nB: They are under the bed.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"des gants",src:"gloves",pos:"noun",gender:"pl",note:"Des gants: gloves (masculine plural).\nOne glove: un gant.\nUsually used in the plural.",example:"A: Il neige dehors!\nB: N'oublie pas tes gants.",exampleSrc:"A: It's snowing outside!\nB: Don't forget your gloves.",funFact:"French nouns are either masculine or feminine. The article gives it away."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"des bottes",src:"boots",pos:"noun",gender:"pl",note:"Des bottes: boots (feminine plural).\nOne boot: une botte.\nDes bottes de pluie: rain boots.",example:"A: Qu'est-ce que tu mets quand il pleut?\nB: Je mets mes bottes.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you wear when it rains?\nB: I put on my boots.",funFact:"Cognate with English 'boots'. Many English words were borrowed from French after 1066."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Vêtements au pluriel",deepDive:"In French, paired items (things that come in twos) are almost always referred to in the plural. This is similar to English 'pants' or 'glasses.' The singular exists but sounds unusual in everyday speech.",text:"Some clothing items are almost always plural:\n- des chaussures (shoes)\n- des chaussettes (socks)\n- des gants (gloves)\n- des bottes (boots)\n- des lunettes (glasses)\n\nYou CAN say une chaussette (one sock), but people normally say des chaussettes.\n\nTo make singular clothing plural:\n- un pull -> des pulls\n- une veste -> des vestes\n- une écharpe -> des écharpes"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Comment dit-on 'a jacket' en français?",opts:["une veste","un veste","une manteau","un pull"],ans:"une veste",hint:"This word is feminine. Think about the article that goes with it."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["un pull","une pull","des pulls","une veste"],hint:"Sweater is masculine in French. Use the right article.",s:"Je porte {1} bleu aujourd'hui. (a sweater)",a:"un pull"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which item is feminine?",opts:["un gant","une écharpe","un pull","un pantalon"],ans:"une écharpe",hint:"Feminine nouns pair with a different article than masculine ones. Check each option."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"une veste",src:"a jacket"},{trg:"un pull",src:"a sweater"},{trg:"une écharpe",src:"a scarf"},{trg:"une ceinture",src:"a belt"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Comment dit-on 'gloves' en français?",opts:["une gant","des gantes","des gants","des mains"],ans:"des gants",hint:"This masculine plural word refers to what you wear on your hands."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["écharpe","veste","pull","ceinture"],hint:"This item is worn around the neck for warmth.",s:"N'oublie pas ton {1}! Il fait froid. (scarf)",a:"écharpe"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Qu'est-ce qu'on met quand il pleut?",opts:["un pull","des gants","une ceinture","des bottes"],ans:"des bottes",hint:"These protect your feet from rain and puddles."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["chaussettes","chaussures","bottes","gants"],hint:"These small items are worn inside your shoes.",s:"Mes {1} sont sous le lit. (socks)",a:"chaussettes"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which of these is usually used in the plural?",opts:["des chaussettes","une veste","un pull","une ceinture"],ans:"des chaussettes",hint:"Think about items that come in pairs for your feet."},
        {type:"drag_fill",hint:"For winter you need warm layers: sweater, scarf, and hand coverings.",s:"Pour l'hiver, je mets {1}, {2} et {3}.",blanks:{"1":"un pull","2":"une écharpe","3":"des gants"},pool:["un pull","une écharpe","des gants","une ceinture"]},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"des chaussettes",src:"socks"},{trg:"des gants",src:"gloves"},{trg:"des bottes",src:"boots"},{trg:"une ceinture",src:"a belt"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"Ce pantalon est trop grand. J'ai besoin d'___.",opts:["une écharpe","une ceinture","des bottes","un pull"],ans:"une ceinture",hint:"This item holds up pants that are too loose."}
  ]},
  {id:"frv2_u8l_a2_rooms_objects",title:"La maison: pièces et objets",icon:"🏠",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"La maison: rooms and household objects",desc:"Learn the remaining rooms of a French home plus essential household objects. These words appear daily in conversation, directions, and descriptions.",goals:["Name 3 key rooms not yet covered","Learn 6 essential household objects","Use propre/sale and ouvert/fermé to describe them"]},
        {type:"teach",trg:"la salle de bain",src:"the bathroom",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine. Literally 'the bath room'.\nSalle de bain has no -s on bain in standard usage.",example:"A: La salle de bain est libre?\nB: Non, j'y suis encore cinq minutes.\nA: D'accord, je patiente.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the bathroom free?\nB: No, I'm still in there five minutes.\nA: OK, I'll wait.",funFact:"French distinguishes la salle de bain (bath/shower room) from les toilettes (toilet room) — they are often separate in French homes."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"la salle à manger",src:"the dining room",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine. Literally 'the room for eating'.\nManger = to eat.",example:"A: On mange dans la cuisine?\nB: Non, la salle à manger est prête.\nA: Super, j'arrive!",exampleSrc:"A: Are we eating in the kitchen?\nB: No, the dining room is ready.\nA: Great, I'm coming!",funFact:"In many French homes, Sunday lunch (le déjeuner du dimanche) in the salle à manger is a cherished family ritual lasting two or three hours."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"le garage",src:"the garage",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine. Cognate with English.\nUsed to park cars and store tools.",example:"A: Où est la voiture?\nB: Dans le garage.\nA: Le garage est ouvert?",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the car?\nB: In the garage.\nA: Is the garage open?",funFact:"Cognate with English 'garage'. Many English words were borrowed from French after 1066."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"la fenêtre",src:"the window",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine. The accent grave on the first -e is important.\nOuvrir la fenêtre = to open the window.",example:"A: Ouvre la fenêtre, s'il te plaît.\nB: La fenêtre du salon?\nA: Oui, il fait chaud.",exampleSrc:"A: Open the window, please.\nB: The living room window?\nA: Yes, it's hot.",funFact:"The word comes from Latin 'fenestra'. It gave English the word 'fenestration' (the design of windows in a building)."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"la porte",src:"the door",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine. La porte d'entrée = front door.\nFermer la porte = to close the door.",example:"A: Ferme la porte!\nB: Pourquoi?\nA: Il y a du vent.",exampleSrc:"A: Close the door!\nB: Why?\nA: It's windy.",funFact:"The word 'port' (harbor) shares the same Latin root 'porta' (gate/entrance) as la porte. Both describe ways in and out."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"la lampe",src:"the lamp",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine. Cognate with English.\nAllumer la lampe = to turn on the lamp.",example:"A: Il fait sombre ici.\nB: Allume la lampe du bureau.\nA: Ah, c'est mieux!",exampleSrc:"A: It's dark in here.\nB: Turn on the desk lamp.\nA: Ah, that's better!",funFact:"Cognate with English 'lamp'. Many English words were borrowed from French after 1066."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"le miroir",src:"the mirror",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine. Typically found in la salle de bain or la chambre.\nSe regarder dans le miroir = to look at oneself in the mirror.",example:"A: Où est le miroir?\nB: Dans la salle de bain.\nA: Merci!",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the mirror?\nB: In the bathroom.\nA: Thanks!",funFact:"The word miroir comes from the Old French 'mirer' (to look at). The English word 'mirror' was borrowed directly from French in the 13th century."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"la clé",src:"the key",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine. Also spelled la clef (older spelling).\nPerdre sa clé = to lose your key.",example:"A: Tu as la clé de la maison?\nB: Oui, voilà la clé.\nA: Merci!",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have the house key?\nB: Yes, here is the key.\nA: Thanks!",funFact:"The word clé gives French several idioms. 'La clé du succès' (the key to success) works in both languages for the same reason."},
        {type:"teach",trg:"le téléphone",src:"the telephone",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine. Cognate with English.\nLe téléphone portable = mobile phone.\nDonner un coup de téléphone = to make a call.",example:"A: Ton téléphone sonne!\nB: Ah oui, c'est ma mère.\nA: Réponds vite!",exampleSrc:"A: Your phone is ringing!\nB: Oh yes, it's my mother.\nA: Answer quickly!",funFact:"Cognate with English 'telephone'. Many English words were borrowed from French after 1066."},
        {type:"tip",title:"Describing rooms and objects: propre/sale and ouvert/fermé",text:"Four essential adjectives for home descriptions:\n\npropre = clean\nsale = dirty\n\nouvert = open (masculine)\nouvert / ouverte = open (feminine)\nfermé = closed (masculine)\nfermé / fermée = closed (feminine)\n\nExamples:\nLa salle de bain est propre. (The bathroom is clean.)\nLa fenêtre est ouverte. (The window is open.)\nLe garage est fermé. (The garage is closed.)\n\nPropre and sale agree in gender: une chambre propre, un bureau sale.",deepDive:"Note that propre placed BEFORE a noun means 'own' (ma propre chambre = my own bedroom). Placed AFTER the noun, it means 'clean' (une chambre propre = a clean bedroom). Context resolves any ambiguity in speech."},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"la salle de bain",src:"the bathroom"},{trg:"la salle à manger",src:"the dining room"},{trg:"le garage",src:"the garage"},{trg:"la fenêtre",src:"the window"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'La salle de bain' literally means:",opts:["The bath room","The dining room","The clean room","The sitting room"],ans:"The bath room",hint:"Salle = enclosed space. Bain = ___. Put them together."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["le miroir","la lampe","la fenêtre","la porte"],hint:"You close THIS to stop the wind. It is the entrance to a room.",s:"Ferme {1}! Il y a du vent.",a:"la porte"},
        {type:"mc",q:"'La fenêtre est ouverte' uses 'ouverte' (not 'ouvert') because:",opts:["La fenêtre is feminine","La fenêtre is plural","Ouverte is always used","La fenêtre starts with a vowel"],ans:"La fenêtre is feminine",hint:"Adjectives agree with the noun's gender. Check the article: 'la' signals which gender."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["la salle à manger","la cuisine","le salon","le bureau"],hint:"The room specifically for eating. Literally 'the room for eating'.",s:"On mange dans {1}.",a:"la salle à manger"},
        {type:"mc",q:"To say the bathroom is dirty, you say:",opts:["La salle de bain est sale","La salle de bain est propre","La salle de bain est fermée","La salle de bain est ouverte"],ans:"La salle de bain est sale",hint:"The opposite of propre (clean) is the word you need."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["le miroir","la clé","la lampe","le téléphone"],hint:"You look at your reflection in this. Found in the bathroom or bedroom.",s:"Je me regarde dans {1}.",a:"le miroir"},
        {type:"fb",opts:["la clé","la lampe","le miroir","la porte"],hint:"You need this to unlock your front door.",s:"Tu as {1} de la maison?",a:"la clé"},
        {type:"fb",opts:["ouvert","ouverte","fermé","fermée"],hint:"The garage is masculine and not open. Which form of closed?",s:"Le garage est {1}.",a:"fermé"},
        {type:"fb",opts:["la fenêtre","la porte","la lampe","la clé"],hint:"It's dark in here. Turn on this light source.",s:"Il fait sombre. Allume {1}!",a:"la lampe"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"la clé",src:"the key"},{trg:"le téléphone",src:"the telephone"},{trg:"la porte",src:"the door"},{trg:"le miroir",src:"the mirror"}]},
        {type:"fb",opts:["le téléphone","la clé","le miroir","la lampe"],hint:"This device rings when someone calls you.",s:"{1} sonne. C'est ma mère!",a:"le téléphone"}
  ]},
  {id:"fre8l8",title:"Révision",icon:"🔄",xp:20,board:true,steps:[
        {type:"intro",title:"Unit 8 Review: A1 Finale",desc:"This is the final A1 unit! Review clothing, colors, numbers, demonstratives, and shopping. You now have survival French for any situation.",goals:["Review all A1.8 vocabulary","Test number skills 20-1000","Combine shopping scenarios"]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Un pantalon' in French is:",opts:["Singular","Plural","Feminine","Invariable"],ans:"Singular",hint:"French treats pants as one garment. Notice the article 'un'."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["blanche","blanc","blancs","blanches"],hint:"White + feminine singular. Irregular form: not just adding -e.",s:"Elle porte une robe {1}. (white, fem.)",a:"blanche"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"une chemise",src:"a shirt"},{trg:"des chaussures",src:"shoes"},{trg:"un manteau",src:"a coat"},{trg:"une jupe",src:"a skirt"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"70 in French is:",opts:["Septante","Soixante-dix","Sept-dix","Soixante-sept"],ans:"Soixante-dix",hint:"60 + 10 = 70 in the standard French system."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Cette","Ce","Cet","Ces"],hint:"That dress (there). Feminine demonstrative.",s:"{1} robe-là est trop chère.",a:"Cette"},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Deux cents' has -s, but 'deux cent un' does not because:",opts:["Un removes the -s","It is irregular","Cent loses -s when followed by another number","Both are correct"],ans:"Cent loses -s when followed by another number",hint:"The -s disappears when more ___ words come after."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["cent","cents","mille","milles"],hint:"300 + 50 = 350. The hundreds word, no -s when followed by more.",s:"Ça coûte trois {1} cinquante euros. (350)",a:"cent"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"rouge",src:"red"},{trg:"bleu",src:"blue"},{trg:"vert",src:"green"},{trg:"noir",src:"black"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Je voudrais essayer ce pantalon en bleu' combines:",opts:["Greeting + clothing + price","Command + article + size","Question + number + color","Polite request + demonstrative + color"],ans:"Polite request + demonstrative + color",hint:"Je voudrais (___) + ce (___) + en bleu (___)."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["Ces","Ce","Cette","Cet"],hint:"These shoes. Plural demonstrative.",s:"{1} chaussures coûtent quatre-vingts euros.",a:"Ces"},
        {type:"mc",q:"At the cash register, 'Ça fait combien?' asks:",opts:["What is the total?","What color is it?","What size is it?","Where is it made?"],ans:"What is the total?",hint:"Ça fait = that comes to. Asking for the ___ price."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["grand","petit","cher","noir"],hint:"This coat is too big. I need smaller.",s:"Ce manteau est trop {1}. Vous avez plus petit?",a:"grand"},
        {type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Combien ça coûte?",src:"How much?"},{trg:"Je voudrais",src:"I would like"},{trg:"essayer",src:"to try on"},{trg:"payer",src:"to pay"}]},
        {type:"mc",q:"'Cet' is used before:",opts:["Feminine nouns","Masculine nouns starting with a vowel","Plural nouns","All nouns"],ans:"Masculine nouns starting with a vowel",hint:"Cet replaces ce for pronunciation before ___/silent h."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["quinze","cinq","dix-cinq","quinz"],hint:"80 + 15 = 95. The word for fifteen.",s:"Quatre-vingt-{1} euros, s'il vous plaît. (95)",a:"quinze"},
        {type:"mc",q:"Which skill did you NOT practice in this first set of units?",opts:["Ordering food at a restaurant","Introducing yourself and family","Writing academic dissertations","Shopping for clothes and groceries"],ans:"Writing academic dissertations",hint:"Think about what daily survival situations you covered versus advanced ___."},
        {type:"fb",opts:["bonne","bon","bonjour","bien"],hint:"Have a good day! Journée is feminine.",s:"Merci beaucoup, {1} journée!",a:"bonne"}
  ]}
